The XRD patterns of N-CDs, NiCo2O4/N-CDs, Ni0.5Co0.5WO4/N-CDs and NiCoP/N-CDs are shown in Fig. 1
                        a. For N-CDs, there is a broad peak at 2θ = 26.6° which is assigned to the (002) plane of carbon with a crystallite size of 1.83 nm and a d-spacing of 0.33 nm (Table 1
                        ). In the case of NiCo2O4/N-CDs, the diffraction peaks centered at 2θ = 30.9°, 36.8°, 44.7°, 58.9° and 65.1° were attributed to the (220), (311), (400), (511) and (440) lattice planes, which is in agreement with the standard diffraction pattern of NiCo2O4 (JCPDS No. 02–4211) [26]. The Ni0.5Co0.5WO4/N-CDs diffraction peaks at 2θ = 30.7°, 35.6°, 41.0°, 44.6°, 53.9° and 65.1° are assigned to (111), (002), (102), (112), (202) and (311) planes which are typical to those of nickel cobalt tungstate [27]. The NiCoP/N-CDs diffraction peaks at 2θ = 28.1°, 36.8°, 44.6°, 51.9°, 59.3° and 65.3° can be indexed to the (110), (200), (111), (201), (210) and (211) reflection planes of NiCoP, indicating the successful loading of NiCoP onto the surface of N-CDs [28]. The suggested growth mechanism of NiCoP onto the surface of N-CDs may be explained as follows. In the first step, the nickel ions reacted with the phosphorous ions to form nickel phosphide. The cobalt ions thereafter substitute some of the nickel sites in nickel phosphide to produce NiCoP nuclei [29]. The NiCoP nuclei eventually aggregate and self-assemble to form NiCoP nanoparticles due to the high surface energy. The full width at half maximum (FWHM) of the main XRD peaks is presented in Table 1. A decrease in the FWHM and an increase in the crystallite size were noticed from N-CDs to NiCoP/N-CDs. These observations can be attributed to the improved crystallinity and enhanced composition homogeneity of NiCoP/N-CDs that has low defect concentration.
